@NODE "What"

@{JCENTER}@{B}@{U}CheckHDParts.rexx - What Is It?@{UB}@{UU}
@{JLEFT}
I had the idea for this script one day when I was part way through a web
browsing session when a @{B}"DISK FULL"@{UB} error message suddenly popped up!

The browser could no longer save web pages to the hard disk cache so that
was the end of that web browsing session :-(

(Wow!! - I just recovered 30 megabytes by deleting junk with just a quick
5 minute look!! :-) - now for a decent spring clean!!)

So, to save me having to try to remember to check how full my hard drive
partitions are all the time, I wrote this script that goes into my
"User-Startup" file. It will now warn me when any partition is over a
preset level of fullness.

You can set, in a preference file, which hard drive partitions you want
included in the check and at what level of fullness you want the warning
given.

For example, you could set the preferences so that, when any partition
reaches 90% full, the warning will be given.

CheckHDParts.rexx does not stay active. After checking the hard drive, it
exits so that no memory is used after the check has been made. Thus the
capacity check is made @{B}ONLY@{UB} on startup.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements"

@{JCENTER}@{B}@{U}CheckHDParts.rexx - Requirements@{UB}@{UU}
@{JLEFT}
To use CheckHDParts.rexx you will need:-

- AmigaDOS/Workbench 2.0 or higher (Does anyone still use WB 1.3 or earlier?)

- ARexx installed on your system

To the best of my knowledge CheckHDParts.rexx will work on @{B}ANY @{UB}Amiga
equipped with AmigaDOS/Workbench 2.0 or higher.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "How"

@{JCENTER}@{B}@{U}CheckHDParts.rexx - How To Use It@{UB}@{UU}
@{JLEFT}
@{B}@{U}Installation Script@{UB}@{UU}:-

This might be included in a future version.

@{B}@{U}Manual Installation@{UB}@{UU}:-

1. Copy "CheckHDParts.rexx" into your assigned Rexx: directory.

2. Copy the file "CheckHDParts.Guide" to wherever you like to keep your
   documents.

3. Edit your "User-Startup" file to include the following line at the @{B}end@{UB}
   of the file, i.e. just before it returns to the "Startup-Sequence" file:-

      RUN >Nil: RX Rexx:CheckHDParts.rexx

3. The first time you boot up after adding the above line the
   "Get Preferences" function of the script will be activated.

   Just follow the prompts that appear in the script's window.

   You will be shown a series of device names that will include your hard
   drive partitions but might also include other device names. You will be
   asked to enter "Y" or "N" to indicate if you want the device name or
   partition being shown to be included in the checks. It may be that some
   hard drive partitions need not be monitored at all.

   Note that some of these device names might @{B}NOT@{UB} be hard drive partitions.
   Floppy drives named DFx: will be filtered out (not shown) as will RAM:
   and RAD: drives but some people may find other device names appearing.
   If they are not hard drive partitions and/or you do not want them
   monitored, then simply enter "N" for them.

   Normally, hard drive partitions are named DHx: where the "x" is the
   device number, e.g. DH0: DH1: etc. However, some hard drives have
   partitions named HD0: HD1: etc. Or there may be some completely 
   different set of names such as AQ0: AQ1: etc. for an AmiQuest hard
   drive. There may well be other variations that I am not familiar with.
   I leave it up to you to select the names of your hard drive partitions.

   You will then be asked to enter a figure that will indicate the level
   of fullness a partition can reach before a warning is given. For example,
   enter 90 if you want the warning when a partition is 90% full, i.e.
   there is only 10% capacity left.

4. On subsequent boots, this preference setting procedure will @{B}NOT@{UB} be
   called.

   Once the preferences have been set, there will be no visual indication
   that the program is working unless a partition's spare capacity drops
   below the preset warning level.

5. To check that it really does work, you could change your preference
   settings (as detailed below) so that a warning is given at a very low
   level of fullness, e.g. 10%. Surely at least one of your partitions will
   be more than 10% full? :-)

6. If you @{B}DO @{UB}carry out the test as per item 5 above, then reset your
   preferences to a more realistic upper level as described below.

@{B}@{U}To Change The Preferences At a Latter Time@{UB}@{UU}

It could well be that you are no longer happy with the preferences that you
entered, or that you have carried out the test mentioned in 5 above.
If so, just enter this command line at a Shell/CLI prompt:-

 RX Rexx:CheckHDParts.rexx NEWPREFS

This will delete the old preferences file and let you enter new
preferences.










































@ENDNODE

